CHAPTER 5 : SYSTEM DESIGN

5.1 System Application Design
The system is designed in layered form:
1. Presentation layer
2. Application/service layer
3. Data access layer
4. Infrastructure and middleware layer

This improves maintainability and keeps business rules isolated from UI and transport concerns.

5.1.1 Method Pseudo Code

Pseudo Code: POS Billing Process
START
  Validate user role and input cart
  Build draft invoice
  Validate stock for each line item
  Apply discounts/coupons
  Save invoice draft
  Capture payment entries
  Post invoice
  Update stock ledger
  Record audit entries
END

Pseudo Code: Return and Refund Process
START
  Validate original invoice and return eligibility
  Process line-level return
  Reverse stock entries
  Record refund transaction
  Save audit trail
END

5.2 Input/Output and Interface Design
Input design prioritizes speed, validation, and role relevance. Output design focuses on invoice readability, reconciliation clarity, and dashboard utility.

5.2.1 Samples of Forms, Reports and Interface
Includes item form, POS billing interface, purchase entry, return form, user form, EOD report, stock ledger report, and dashboard cards.

5.2.2 State Diagram
State flow covers Draft, Posted, PartiallyPaid, Paid, ReturnInitiated, Refunded, and Closed states.


CHAPTER 6 : IMPLEMENTATION PLANNING

6.1 Implementation Environment
Implementation was carried out in a practical environment with local development, containerized execution, and production validation workflows.

6.2 Modules Specification
Implemented modules:
1. Authentication and user management
2. Foundation master data
3. Stock transaction ledger
4. POS billing
5. Payments
6. Returns and refunds
7. Loyalty and coupons
8. Purchase management
9. Invoice management
10. EOD reports
11. Dashboard
12. Audit trail
13. Offline sync queue

6.3 Security Features
1. Identity and role-based authorization
2. Anti-forgery protection
3. Secure headers and CSP
4. Rate limiting on sensitive endpoints
5. Startup validation for critical production secrets
6. Audit and correlation-based tracing

6.4 Coding Standard
1. Layered separation of concerns
2. Clear naming conventions
3. Validation-first approach
4. Async programming on I/O paths
5. Structured logging and safe error handling
6. Test and documentation discipline


CHAPTER 7 : TESTING

7.1 Testing Plan
Testing objective is to verify business correctness, security integrity, integration reliability, and deployment readiness.

Entry criteria:
1. Successful build
2. Valid test environment and seeded data
3. Required modules reachable

Exit criteria:
1. Critical suites pass
2. No blocking security defects
3. Smoke checks pass after deployment

7.2 Testing Strategy
A hybrid strategy was used:
1. Automated tests for service logic, integration, and security regression
2. Manual tests for module workflow and UI behavior
3. Risk-based focus on billing, stock, authentication, and returns

Current discovered automated baseline:
- Total [Fact]/[Theory] tests: 70
- Largest suite: POS billing tests
- Strong integration and security regression coverage

7.3 Test Suites Design

Professional Test Suite Matrix:
1. Authentication and Access Suite
2. User and Role Governance Suite
3. Master Data Integrity Suite
4. Stock Ledger Consistency Suite
5. POS Billing Core Suite
6. Payment Processing Suite
7. Returns and Refund Suite
8. Loyalty and Coupon Rule Suite
9. Purchase and Receiving Suite
10. Reporting and EOD Suite
11. Security Hardening Suite
12. API and Middleware Suite
13. Performance and Stability Suite
14. Deployment Smoke Suite

Each suite follows a common template:
- Scenario ID
- Precondition
- Steps
- Expected Result
- Actual Result
- Status
- Evidence and defect reference


CHAPTER 8 : CONCLUSION AND DISCUSSION

8.1 Self Analysis of Project Viabilities
Technical and operational viability are high due to modular design, strong feature implementation, and practical deployment experience. Economic viability is favorable for small to medium retail business scenarios.

8.2 Problem Encountered and Possible Solutions
Major issues included deployment permissions, security-flow troubleshooting, and environment-level inconsistencies. Solutions were implemented through runbook improvements, regression validation, and phased hardening.

8.3 Summary of Project Work
The project successfully delivered an integrated retail ERP solution covering core operational modules, security controls, testing maturity, and production-oriented documentation. It demonstrates practical readiness and extensibility for future growth.


CHAPTER 9 : LIMITATION AND FUTURE ENHANCEMENT

9.1 Limitations
1. Uneven automation depth across all modules.
2. Offline sync maturity needs broader validation.
3. Production automation depends on environment permissions.
4. Advanced analytics and mobile support are limited in current scope.

9.2 Future Enhancement
1. Expand full regression automation.
2. Add advanced analytics and forecasting.
3. Strengthen offline sync conflict handling.
4. Improve HA/DR deployment maturity.
5. Build role-focused mobile companion support.
6. Add deeper third-party enterprise integrations.

9.3 Final Note
This project is a strong, practical base that can evolve into a commercially robust ERP platform with the above enhancements.


